text:
JONESBORO - Lots of students are in JROTC.

There are more than 880 Air Force units throughout the world. There are units
throughout high schools in the U.S. and military bases across the globe.

But Jonesboro's Laityn Tippy is the only cadet on the planet who the Air Force
recognized as its top high school member for her leadership and skill.

Tippy, who is the commander of her unit, attends Westside High School. Tippy,
17 and only the second cadet to receive the award, plans to apply for the
United States Air Force Academy, the nation's higher-education option
dedicated to training Air Force officers in Colorado Springs.

She said she's thankful for the opportunities in community service and the
privilege to lead her unit.

Tippy didn't join JROTC, which stands for Junior Reserve Officer Training
Corps and is dedicated to high school students, for recognition, she said.

"I'm just really thankful we have a really good JROTC unit and that our
instructors relay actually care about us," Tippy said, crediting her
instructor Maj. Scott Norman, the senior aerospace science instructor at
Westside High School.

Norman said Tippy is renowned for her humble attitude and focus on service.

"When I called she said 'what did you do to deserve this?' I said 'I don't
think you realize how awesome you are,'" Norman said about when he let her
know that she won the national award.

Tippy keeps the cadet-run unit that she leads in tip-top shape.

The cadet has maintained at least a 4.0 throughout her high school days, and
she's on student council. Tippy has also taken numerous Advanced Placement
courses designated for students to college credit and she's on the National
Honor Society.

The girl is someone who all teachers know as a good student and good person,
Norman said.

"If you ask any of the teachers at Westside High School, they can't say enough
kind things about her," Norman said.

Her willingness to serve the community is part of why the Air Force awarded
Tippy the honor.

"They really don't like to see somebody be just in JROTC," Norman said. "They
want to see somebody who's a leader throughout the school."

Norman called Tippy the best cadet he's seen in his seven years instructing
JROTC.

"I'm most impressed with students who show maturity beyond their years,"
Norman said, noting that Tippy is always professional when it comes to leading
her unit.

Norman nominated Tippy for the award, and last year, he nominated Luke Walz,
who was awarded the honor at the state level.

Walz has been accepted to the Air Force Academy, where Tippy plans to apply.

"That was usually one of the things that my interviewers would say something
about," Walz said, stating that the award was one of the reasons he was
accepted into the academy.

He said he expects that with an award recognizing Tippy as the best cadet in
the world, she'll sail through the application process.

"Oh it'll be super helpful, like national cadet No. 1 that's like insane,
especially from a little town in Arkansas," Walz said. He also called her an
amazing person.

Tippy said she's excited to join the military and serve the American people.

"I think the adventure you get in the military is an experience you don't get
anywhere else," Tippy said.

Tippy has dreamed of being a pilot her whole life.

"Like hundreds of years ago, no one was doing this, and we have the freedom
to, so I want to protect that freedom," Tippy said about flying.
